        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a cheerful 4-year-old boy from Brno, Czech Republic, who attends a local kindergarten five days a week. He has curly brown hair, rosy cheeks when healthy, and a love of toy trains and playing in the sandbox with friends. His parents — a nurse mother and an engineer father — describe him as sociable and full of energy under normal circumstances.\n\nOver the past four days, {patientName} has been increasingly unwell. He developed a persistent, productive cough that brings up thick, yellow-tinged mucus [MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9], accompanied by audible wheezing when he breathes [SNOMED:J20.9, MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9]. His mother notes he has had episodes of appearing to choke on phlegm, which has been distressing for the whole family [SNOMED:J20.9]. He also has a low-grade fever and general fatigue [MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9], and has complained of a stomach ache on two occasions [SNOMED:J20.9].\n\nAt rest {patientName} looks slightly pale and tired. His breathing is slightly laboured during activity — even walking across the room makes him short of breath [MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9]. He is less interested in eating but still drinking well. His parents have been giving him paracetamol at home to help with the fever [MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9].\n\n{patientName} usually enjoys outdoor play in the local park, helping his grandmother water the garden, and watching animated films with his older sister. He has not been exposed to tobacco smoke at home. His kindergarten group recently had a wave of colds circulating among the children, and {patientName}'s symptoms began shortly after several classmates were ill [MEDLINEPLUS:J20.9]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
